<p>
  Whether you're writing a 500-word blog post, a 280-character tweet, or a 10,000-word report, knowing your word count matters. Word limits exist for good reasons: SEO best practices, academic submission rules, social media character caps, and publisher guidelines all set expectations around length. This guide explains how to count words online for free, why it matters, and how to hit your target every time.
</p>

<h2>Why Word Count Matters</h2>

<p>
  Word count is one of the most commonly required metrics across writing contexts. Here's where it shows up:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>SEO and blogging:</strong> Google tends to rank longer, more thorough content higher for competitive keywords. Most SEO guidelines recommend at least 1,500 words for posts targeting search rankings.</li>
  <li><strong>Academic writing:</strong> University essays and dissertations specify exact word ranges. Going over or under by more than 10% can result in grade penalties.</li>
  <li><strong>Social media:</strong> Twitter/X limits tweets to 280 characters. LinkedIn posts perform best at 150–300 words. Instagram captions cap at 2,200 characters.</li>
  <li><strong>Publishing and journalism:</strong> Magazines and newspapers specify word counts for feature articles, op-eds, and reviews.</li>
  <li><strong>Creative writing:</strong> Short stories, flash fiction, and contest submissions often have strict word limits (e.g., "under 1,000 words").</li>
</ul>

