<h2>Word Count vs Character Count</h2>

<p>
  These two metrics measure different things. <strong>Word count</strong> counts the number of words in your text (separated by spaces). <strong>Character count</strong> counts every individual character, including letters, spaces, punctuation, and numbers.
</p>

<p>
  Use <strong>word count</strong> when: writing for academic submissions, content marketing, publishing, or any context where the reader experience (how long it takes to read) is the concern.
</p>

<p>
  Use <strong>character count</strong> when: writing for SMS (160 characters per message), social media platforms, form fields with character limits, or meta descriptions (ideally under 155 characters for SEO).
</p>

<h2>Word Counts for Different Types of Content</h2>

<p>Here's a practical reference for common writing formats:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Tweet / X post:</strong> up to 280 characters</li>
  <li><strong>Meta description:</strong> 120–155 characters (about 20–25 words)</li>
  <li><strong>Email subject line:</strong> 40–60 characters (6–10 words)</li>
  <li><strong>Blog post (short):</strong> 500–800 words</li>
  <li><strong>Blog post (standard):</strong> 1,500–2,500 words</li>
  <li><strong>Long-form pillar article:</strong> 3,000–5,000+ words</li>
  <li><strong>Short story:</strong> 1,000–7,500 words</li>
  <li><strong>Novella:</strong> 20,000–40,000 words</li>
  <li><strong>Novel:</strong> 70,000–100,000 words</li>
  <li><strong>University essay:</strong> typically 1,500–5,000 words</li>
</ul>

<h2>Tips for Hitting a Word Count Target</h2>

<p>
  If you're writing to a specific length, here are practical strategies:
</p>

<h3>To increase word count</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Add more examples and case studies to each point</li>
  <li>Expand each section with "why it matters" explanations</li>
  <li>Include a FAQ section (this also helps with SEO rich results)</li>
  <li>Add a comparison table or numbered list</li>
  <li>Link out to related topics and briefly explain the connection</li>
</ul>

<h3>To reduce word count</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Remove filler phrases like "it is worth noting that", "in order to", and "due to the fact that"</li>
  <li>Replace passive voice with active voice (saves 2–4 words per sentence)</li>
  <li>Cut adverbs and replace with stronger verbs ("ran quickly" → "sprinted")</li>
  <li>Remove redundant adjectives ("completely finished" → "finished")</li>
  <li>Use the <a href="/tools/word-counter">word counter</a> while editing to track your progress in real time</li>
</ul>

<h2>Word Count in Google Docs, Word, and Notion</h2>

<p>
  Most writing apps have built-in word counts, but they vary in features:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Google Docs:</strong> Tools → Word count (Ctrl+Shift+C). Shows words, characters with and without spaces, and page count.</li>
  <li><strong>Microsoft Word:</strong> The status bar at the bottom shows live word count. Tools → Word Count for full stats.</li>
  <li><strong>Notion:</strong> No built-in word counter. Use a browser-based tool like TextWonder for accurate counts.</li>
  <li><strong>VS Code / plain text:</strong> No built-in counter. Paste into TextWonder to count instantly.</li>
</ul>

